{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17933"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17933"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.33,0.06,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72919"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10647"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24807"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72919"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EObesity is a well recognised risk factor for a number of cancers. This is particularly the case for men with type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Obese men with type 2 diabetes are at risk of all the following cancers EXCEPT?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colorectal cancer","Liver cancer","Oesophageal cancer","Pancreatic cancer","Prostate cancer"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EObesity and type 2 diabetes are known risk factors for several types of cancer. These conditions are associated with increased levels of insulin and insulin-like growth factors, which can promote cancer cell growth. Additionally, obesity is linked to chronic inflammation, which can contribute to cancer development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E risk is increased in individuals with obesity and type 2 diabetes due to factors such as insulin resistance and chronic inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is also associated with obesity and type 2 diabetes, as these conditions can lead to changes in insulin and glucose metabolism that may promote cancer development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cancer\u003C/strong\u003E risk is elevated in patients with obesity and type 2 diabetes, often due to the development of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease and subsequent cirrhosis, which are common in these populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E (adenocarcinoma) is increased in men with obesity and type 2 diabetes. This might be related to the increased incidence of gastro-oesophageal reflux, with the development of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus, which in turn increases the risk of malignant change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate cancer\u003C/strong\u003E risk is not significantly elevated in patients with obesity and type 2 diabetes. Some studies suggest that these conditions may even be associated with a lower risk of prostate cancer, possibly due to lower testosterone levels in obese men.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obesity and type 2 diabetes are associated with an increased risk of several cancers, including colorectal cancer.","Prostate cancer risk is not significantly elevated in patients with obesity and type 2 diabetes."],"references":["Fernandez CJ, George AS, Subrahmanyan NA, Pappachan JM. Epidemiological link between obesity, type 2 diabetes mellitus and cancer. World J Methodol. 2021 May 20;11(3):23-45. doi: 10.5662/wjm.v11.i3.23. PMID: 34026577; PMCID: PMC8127420.","Scully T, Ettela A, LeRoith D, Gallagher EJ. Obesity, Type 2 Diabetes, and Cancer Risk. Front Oncol. 2021 Feb 2;10:615375. doi: 10.3389/fonc.2020.615375. PMID: 33604295; PMCID: PMC7884814.","Scully T, Ettela A, LeRoith D, Gallagher EJ. Obesity, Type 2 Diabetes, and Cancer Risk. Front Oncol. 2021 Feb 2;10:615375. doi: 10.3389/fonc.2020.615375. PMID: 33604295; PMCID: PMC7884814.","Gallagher EJ, LeRoith D. Obesity and Diabetes: The Increased Risk of Cancer and Cancer-Related Mortality. Physiol Rev. 2015 Jul;95(3):727-48. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00030.2014. PMID: 26084689; PMCID: PMC4491542."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17933"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T17:33:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T17:33:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10647"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72919"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical m